why we dont need grandmother neurons - howard blair

there is a subject that saw pictures of his grandmother and htey monitored the neurons that fired.  there was a particular neuron that fired when he saw his grandmother neuron.  the idea is that everything we have learned and store in our brain is coded in a neuron or a group of neurons.  the firing of the neurons create tehse memories or something.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grandmother_cell

he (blair) is not arguing that it is wrong, he is arguing that we can account for mental things based on other phenominon.

(aside, how do you ontologically characterize abstract structures?)

analogy between laptop and brain.  we deal with computer programs running on the laptop, not the electrical phenomina of the physical laptop.  the running time of the program allows us to do far more complex phenomina than the simple underlying physics.

10^15 neuro connections or something something about around 10^18 or 10^20 for connections.

