Chlamydomonas Reinhardtii

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chlamydomonas_reinhardtii

the animal is fast for its size.  it attracts toward certain frequencies of light and is repeled against certain frequencies of light (as associated with food or preditors).

the animal can do more complicated things that whatits raw structure suggests.  it might be able to do this based on nonlinear dynamics.  for this to be true, it would have to have a feedback mechanism, which it does.


showed the image from blackboard:
juliaUVBox copy.gif

two dots with directed, connected lines both ways between them. 

say the left is U and the right is V

the arrow head indicates what can read.  u can read v on two channels and v can read u on two channels.

u_t+1 = v_t | v_t
      = 1 - (v_t)^2

v_t+1 = 1 - (u_t)^2

what happens when you iterate based on this formula?  see the image.

if you initialize u or v to anything in the white value outside the square will blow up to infinity exponentially.  any value in the blue region will bounce around in the blue region until it converges (same for red, but htey converge to different values)  blue will go to (1,0) and red will go to (0, 1)  it can bounce between different blue/red regions but it will stay within its color.  anything in the color doesnt bounce at random, it will converge to bounce between 0,0 and 1,1 and continue bouncing back and forth between them.

top right corner is the "golden ratio".

talked about squareNormCobit.gif

he talked about chip yeilds being abysmal.  chips come out without working at all and have to be embedded in error correction chips.  can you make an architecture that can handle errors though?

attractors can do this by allowing things to be within the basis of attraction when going into the next stage of the chip.

maybe the values will be wrong, but the relationship between then could be the same.  going back to the square colored image, if its not perfect, the squares would become slurred, but hey would still be relationally the same.  as long as its not hte actual values (voltages) that hold state, use the relationship instead and you can create a higher yeild.


