https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton's_method

see image v1.


imagine a quadratic formula:

ax^2 + bx + c  (this is all of them)

lets reduce:

ax^2+bx
now a+b=1

f(x)=(1-b)x^2+bx
f'(0)=b

if the derivative at the fixed point is less than 1 it is an attractor.  if it is grater than one it is a repeller.

he went into a really complicated diatribe about how to make switching functions.

one of the problems iwth neutons method is that you can really freakin miss pretty hard core.

with respect to neutons method, these roots are attractors and htey have a basis of attraction.  (bason of attraction?)

what are the boundries typically alike in these situations?  they are like fractals.

